\subsection{Language-level findings}

\paragraph{English}

Weak spurious correlation toward old-fashioned looking images with the prompt of &quot;photograph&quot;

\paragraph{Spanish}

Anything?

\paragraph{German}

Anything?

\paragraph{Chinese}

Surprising degree of poor performance on the non-Chinese-trained models. INVESTIGATE IF I CAN GET LID DISTRIBUTION FOR DATA IN LAION. Might be a product of the segregated nature of the Chinese internet. DallE mini/mega has a general bias toward producing photographs, DallE 2 is singularly able to produce coherent outputs for the English models. On occasional collisions (sometimes caused by mistranslations) sensical errors are made (e.g., Mao Zedong for hair) which amusingly, isn&#039;t an error that CogView2 makes. (Not trained on any political images?)

Furthermore, the Mao \inlinezh{毛} example is evidence that while this approach excels at providing a high-level assessment of multilingual conceptual coverage, consideration has to be given to mistranslations in drawing fine-grained conclusions about the coverage of specific concepts.

\paragraph{Japanese}

Bias toward generating faces in DalleMini/Mega. Bias toward sexualization of female pictures, e.g. \inlinejp{女の子}, lots of high-specificity collisions, might be having problems exacerbated by the shared character set between CJ.

\paragraph{Hebrew}

Models consistently bad at Hebrew. Interestingly, they exhibit uniform collision cases (nondescript Israeli city block images, landscapes, etc)

DallE2 likes to generate Menorahs and Israel flags for example (mother, shirt, world)


\paragraph{Indonesian}

Orang/Orangutan/orange collision

Generally good, probably due to Latin alphabet



